{"title_page": "New Surrender", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = New Surrender\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Anberlin]]\n| cover      = Newsurrender cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 30, 2008\n| recorded   = February\u2013May 2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[NRG Recording Studios]], [[North Hollywood]], [[California]]\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]]\n| length     = 45:04\n| label      = [[The Universal Motown/Universal Republic Group|Universal Republic]]\n| producer   = [[Neal Avron]]\n| prev_title = [[Lost Songs (Anberlin album)|Lost Songs]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Dark is the Way, Light is a Place]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = {{nowrap|New Surrender}}\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Feel Good Drag]]\n | single1date = August 18, 2008 (Digital) August 26, 2008 (Radio)\n | single2     = [[Breaking (song)|Breaking]]\n | single2date = June 29, 2009 (Radio)\n | single3     = [[True Faith (Anberlin song)|True Faith]]\n | single3date = September 1, 2009 (Digital) <small>(Deluxe edition re-release)</small>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''New Surrender''''' is the fourth studio album by American [[alternative rock]] band [[Anberlin]], released on September 30, 2008.<ref name=abspunkrelease>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/calendar.php?do=getinfo&e=4710&c=3|title=Release Dates: Anberlin - New Surrender|accessdate=May 30, 2008}}</ref> It is the band's first album on a major label, after signing with [[The Universal Motown/Universal Republic Group|Universal Republic Records]] on August 16, 2007.<ref name=univ>{{cite web|url=http://www.universalrepublic.com/ArtistProfile.aspx?A=834 |title=Florida Indie Rockers Anberlin Hit Studio for Universal Republic Debut |publisher=Universal Republic.com |accessdate=June 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018050700/http://www.universalrepublic.com/ArtistProfile.aspx?A=834 |archivedate=October 18, 2007 }}</ref> The album peaked at number 13 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and 5 on the ''Billboard'' Top Modern Rock / Alternative Albums chart.\n\nAnberlin went in to record their fourth album only twelve months after the 2007 release of their third, ''[[Cities (Anberlin album)|Cities]]''. The album was recorded at [[NRG Recording Studios]] in [[North Hollywood]], [[California]], in early 2008 by producer Neal Avron.<ref name=musicrem>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicremedy.com/a/Anberlin/album/New_Surrender-5410.html|title=Anberlin - New Surrender|publisher=Music-Remedy.com|accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref> The first single from the album, \"[[Feel Good Drag]]\" was originally set to be released to radio prior to the album on August 18, 2008,<ref name=\"single\">{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=416761|title=Radio Date for New Anberlin Single|publisher=Absolute Punk.net|last=DeAndrea|first=Joe|date=July 18, 2008|accessdate=July 18, 2008}}</ref> but was pushed back to August 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=494381|title=Feel Good About Helping Anberlin|publisher=AbsolutePunk.net|accessdate=January 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Background===\nAnberlin set about doing two weeks of pre-production for ''New Surrender'', a significant amount more than the four days they did with ''[[Cities (Anberlin album)|Cities]]''. Guitarist Joseph Milligan said the pre-production comprised them \"playing in a room, playing all the new songs together and working on parts together. We would tweak things here and there.\"<ref name=ulti/> He also said the extra time allowed more input from the other band members, \"everybody tossed in ideas. It was something we had never really had before. It was definitely a group effort.\" The two weeks enabled Milligan and fellow guitarist [[Christian McAlhaney]] to weed down the original 24 songs they had, to just 17, before moving into the studio and [[multitrack recording|tracking]] 15.<ref name=ulti/>\n\n===Writing and recording===\nLead vocalist [[Stephen Christian]], who is also the main lyricist for Anberlin, has said that he wrote a portion of the fourth album while on a trip to [[New Orleans]], at a small cafe named Kahve.<ref name=anberlinofficialblog2>{{cite web|url=http://community.anberlin.com/viewtopic.php?t=5304|title=New Surrender Studio Journal: Recording|publisher=Anberlin.com|date=February 1, 2008|last=Christian|first=Stephen|accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref> Christian said \"the pressures were immense\" after signing with Universal, and that he had a \"minor breakdown\" leading him to \"run away to New Orleans\" in February to write a couple of songs for the record.<ref name=billb>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044013/anberlin-sidesteps-pressure-on-universal-debut|title=Anberlin Sidesteps Pressure On Universal|publisher=Billboard.com|last=Graff|first=Gary|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2008}}</ref> Reminiscing over the experience he added, \"the songs that came from the trip, inspired by New Orleans, are like none other before\".<ref name=anberlinofficialblog2/>\n\nIn an interview with Hurley Blog, Stephen Christian stated his top five lyrical influences for the album have been: \"1. The war (in [[Iraq War|Iraq]]) 2. Revelations/conspiracy theories 3. Recent news that one of our close friends has been diagnosed with what could be a terminal disease 4. My time spent in New Orleans 5. My current relationship.\"<ref name=hurley>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurley.com/blog.cfm/aid/10533|title=Anberlin In-studio Interview|date=February 13, 2008|publisher=Hurley Blog|accessdate=July 24, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203180157/http://www.hurley.com/blog.cfm/aid/10533|archive-date=February 3, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rhythm guitarist [[Christian McAlhaney]] has made his debut as a songwriter on the album; Stephen Christian said \"He is an incredible counterpoint to Joseph Milligan and has written several songs that are going to be on this record!.\".<ref name=hurley/>\n\nAfter years of work with friend and producer Aaron Sprinkle, the band opted for change and along with Universal Republic, selected notable producer Neal Avron. Avron has been involved in the genre for years, producing albums for [[Yellowcard]], [[New Found Glory]] and [[Fall Out Boy]].<ref name=musicrem/> The band completed pre-production on February 11\u201329, 2008, cutting down from the original 26 songs to just 15,<ref name=anberlinofficialblog>{{cite web|url=http://community.anberlin.com/viewtopic.php?t=5335|title=New Surrender Studio Journal: Speak for Yourself|publisher=Anberlin.com|date=March 1, 2008|last=Rexroat|first=Deon|accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref>\nincidentally by turning four songs into a single one.<ref name=anberlinofficialblog1>{{cite web|url=http://community.anberlin.com/viewtopic.php?t=5350|title=New Surrender Studio Journal: Home|publisher=Anberlin.com|date=March 12, 2008|last=Young|first=Nathan|accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  =\"We will all come to the point in our life where we have to admit that we feel defeated, that something has conquered us. We must change, not because we want to, but because we desperately have to. We can not take life in its current suffocating state, even to admit such desperation shows that we are feeling deserted, wandering the barren desert, a shell of our former selves. It is only up from here, it is impossible to sink any lower into ourselves or our circumstances. But we can be salvaged, a deliverance. No vice can stand, no fix can take. The thorn in the side can be removed, but you have to be willing to admit and surrender. Surrender your habits, your lifestyle, your past, your present, and your future. This is your new surrender. The new surrender. New Surrender.\"\n | source =\u2014[[Stephen Christian]], Anberlin lyricist and vocalist, on the title ''New Surrender''<ref name=title/>\n | width  =33%\n | align  =right\n}}\n\nThe actual recording and production took place at multiple studios in [[Hollywood]], [[California]], under Avron throughout March and early April 2008. The first recording took place at Swing House Recordings in [[West Hollywood]], followed by [[NRG Recording Studios]] in [[North Hollywood]], where they completed at lot of the drum tracks and began the bass and guitar tracks. Finally they completed recording at The Boat Studio in [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles, California|Silver Lake]], where the main focus was the vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anberlin.buzznet.com/user/video/3155461/buzznet-rides-boat-anberlin/|title=Buzznet rides the boat with Anberlin|publisher=Buzznet|accessdate=January 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605024940/http://anberlin.buzznet.com/user/video/3155461/buzznet-rides-boat-anberlin/|archive-date=June 5, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe band stated in a webchat session with [[AbsolutePunk.net]] that they would be using a wide range of instruments including the [[sitar]], this claim was later declared as a joke, with Joseph Milligan saying, \"It was a joke! There\u2019s no sitar! Now I kind of wish there was so that we could actually say that!\"<ref name=ulti>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/anberlin_new_surrender_was_definitely_a_group_effort.html|title=Anberlin: New Surrender 'Was Definitely A Group Effort'|accessdate=October 22, 2008|date=October 2, 2008|publisher=Ultimate Guitar}}</ref>\n\n===Title===\nThe album's mysterious title has been explained multiple times by Anberlin's lyricist Christian. He has said the title explains people's need to give things up to change, \"In everybody's life, there's something they know they have to give up... There's something they have to change or take care of in their lives to progress to the next step.\"<ref name=live>{{cite web|url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/15087.html|title=Anberlin frontman hopes listeners look beyond labels|publisher=Live Daily|accessdate=November 4, 2008|date=October 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023210404/http://www.livedaily.com/news/15087.html|archive-date=October 23, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> His original explanation on the band's [[Myspace]] blog quickly spread across music news sites, with them reporting his insight on the title and how \"we must change, not because we want to, but because we desperately have to.\"<ref name=title>{{cite web|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/news/2008/04/20.Anberlin%20Explains%20New%20Album%20Title.asp|title=Anberlin Explains New Album Title|date=April 19, 2008|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nChristian alluded to the title's power, \"I think it's a motivational speech, in two words... Hopefully, [''New Surrender''] is that motivational speech in 40 minutes.\"<ref name=live/>\n\n==Promotion==\nA pre-order for the upcoming album was available throughout the 2008 [[Warped Tour]] in the [[United States|US]]. [[Anberlin]] was showcasing their new material on the [[Warped Tour#Stages|main stage]] for the entire tour, with the pre-order coming with a [[USB]] device on a wristband. The USB contained a direct link to a [[Music download|digital download]] of the album, available on the release date September 30, 2008. The USB also had four exclusive tracks, including an alternate acoustic remix of \"Breaking\", and remixes of \"Hello Alone\", \"[[The Unwinding Cable Car]]\" and \"[[Feel Good Drag|The Feel Good Drag]]\".<ref name=preorder>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=352941|title=Anberlin New Surrender Pre-Order Info|publisher=Absolute Punk.net|last=Djamoos|first=Anton|date=June 19, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn response to some fans who claimed Anberlin was selling out, the band members released a music video called \"Compound Lockdown\". Christian McAlhaney introduced the video by saying that Anberlin \"likes money a lot\" and was going in a different direction, more towards a \"hip-hop, thug rap, dirty south kind of thing\". The song \"Drop Dat (Did You?)\" comes on next, displaying Stephen Christian and the members of Anberlin, accompanied by Vic Fuentes of [[Pierce the Veil]] and members of [[Four Year Strong]], rapping to the song. This, of course, is meant to be taken lightly as a joke.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[About.com]]\n|rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=abt>{{cite web |url=http://rock.about.com/od/reviews/fr/newsurrender.htm |title=Anberlin New Surrender Review |last=Grierson |first=Tim |date=September 30, 2008 |publisher=About.com |accessdate=January 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n|rev2 =  [[AbsolutePunk]]\n|rev2score = 79%<ref name=ap>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=507501|title=Anberlin - New Surrender|publisher=[[AbsolutePunk.net]]|accessdate=October 8, 2008|first=Blake|last=Solomon|date=August 27, 2008}}</ref>\n|rev3 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev3score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=am>{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1408321|pure_url=yes}}|title=New Surrender|first=Jared|last=Johnson|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=July 20, 2009}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n|rev4score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news  | title = Anberlin - New Surrender  | newspaper = [[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]  | pages =   | date = October 2008  | url =  | postscript = <!--None--> }} Issue #243</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[CCM Magazine]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=ccm>{{cite web |url=http://www.newreleasetuesday.com/userprofile_reviewssinglepost.php?review_id=10060&user_id=16356 |title=An Emotional Crossover Sure to Yield Superstardom |last=Argyrakis |first=Andy |date=November 24, 2008 |work=CCM Magazine |accessdate=January 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Christianity Today]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=ct>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/reviews/2008/newsurrender.html |title='''Anberlin:''' New Surrender |last=Breimeier |first=Russ |date=September 2008 |work=Christianity Today |accessdate=January 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903203159/http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/reviews/2008/newsurrender.html |archivedate=September 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n|rev7 = [[Cross Rhythms]]\n|rev7Score = {{rating|10|10|full=U+25A0.svg|empty=Solid white borderedS.svg|rating=square}}<ref name=cr>{{cite web |url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/products/Anberlin/New_Surrender/79267/ |title=Review: New Surrender - Anberlin |last=Cummings |first=Tony |authorlink=Tony Cummings |date=November 22, 2010 |publisher=Cross Rhythms |accessdate=January 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n|rev8 = Jesus Freak Hideout\n|rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=jfh>{{cite web|url=http://jesusfreakhideout.com/cdreviews/NewSurrender.asp|title=Anberlin - New Surrender|publisher=Jesus Freak Hideout|first=Lindsay|last=Wiseman|date=September 28, 2008|accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n|rev9 = [[Melodic (magazine)|Melodic]]\n|rev9score= {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=net>{{cite web|url=http://www.melodic.net/?page=review&id=6106|title=Anberlin - ''New Surrender'' |last=Roth|first=Kaj|date=2008|publisher=Melodic|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>\n|rev10 = Patrol Magazine\n|rev10score = 7.1/10<ref name=pm>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrolmag.com/music/760/anberlin-new-surrender/|title=Anberlin - New Surrender|work=[[Patrol magazine]]|date=September 29, 2008|first=David|last=Sessions| accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n|rev11 = The Phantom Tollbooth\n|rev11score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=tpt>{{cite web |url=http://www.tollbooth.org/2009/reviews/anberlin.html |title=Review of The Phantom Tollbooth |last=Morovich |first=James |date=December 30, 2008 |publisher=The Phantom Tollbooth |accessdate=January 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n''New Surrender'' received critical acclaim from [[Music journalism|music critics]], with many alluding to the fact it is their major label debut, and has been successful musically. [[Allmusic]]'s Jared Johnson gave the album 4.5/5, calling ''New Surrender'' Anberlin's \"best sense of direction yet\" and said the album wasn't \"as much a diversion as it is a realization of their potential to finally seize the full emo spirit in all its glory\".<ref name=am /> Lindsay Wiseman of Jesus Freak Hideout said, \"Much respect is deserved and given to Anberlin for making the always-risky move to a major record company...  Through the differences you will find, you will see these changes are not necessarily negative. At the heart of this album, you know it's still Anberlin.\"<ref name=jfh /> [[AbsolutePunk]]'s writer Blake Solomon said he \"was forced to deal with some devastating news: Anberlin has signed to a major label,\" going onto reveal, \"Of course it\u2019s just my luck that ''New Surrender'' rocks with the force of ''[[Blueprints for the Black Market|Blueprints]] (for the Blackmarket)'' and smarts of ''[[Never Take Friendship Personal]]''.\"<ref name=ap /> Patrol Magazine's David Sessions gave the album a 7.1/10, after being especially impressed by the opening track. \"Like last time, New Surrender opens with a stunning, rocketing, riot-igniting send-off, except that \u201cThe Resistance\u201d knocks \u201c[[Godspeed EP|Godspeed]]\u201d flat on its back, immediately demanding to be named Best Anberlin Track Ever.\"<ref name=pm />\n\n[[Tony Cummings]] of [[Cross Rhythms]] gave it a 10/10, alluding to how \"Predictably non-Christian critics sneer at Anberlin, [[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo magazine]] recently decrying, that 'painfully sincere emoting'\", which is why he \"can only suggest Cross Rhythms readers take the advice of the vocal hook on 'The Resistance' and 'Think for yourself.'\"<ref name=cr /> At ''[[CCM Magazine]]'', Andy Argyrakis gave it a 5/5, saying that \"Long story short, New Surrender is hands-down one of 2008\u2019s most essential albums to own and is sure to position Anberlin as much deserved cross-cultural superstars.\"<ref name=ccm /> Tim Grierson of [[About.com]] gave it a 3.5/5, commenting that \"''New Surrender'' may lack the rough edges of earlier Anberlin efforts, but its sleek musicianship and heartfelt songs are significant compensation.\"<ref name=abt /> At ''[[Christianity Today]]'', Russ Breimeier gave it 4.5/5, referencing that \"though ''Cities'' will undoubtedly remain the favorite to many, these ears can't help but appreciate ''New Surrender'' as Anberlin's most varied and mature album to date.\"<ref name=ct /> James Morovich of The Phantom Tollbooth gave it a 4/5, noting how ''Cities'' will be the best the band put out, but noting that \"this album does nothing to take away me calling them one of the best Alternative Rock bands writing music right now.\"<ref name=tpt /> At [[Melodic (magazine)|Melodic]], Kaj Roth gave it a 3.5/5, saying the band have \"deliver[ed] a set of mighty fine songs.\"<ref name=net />\n\n===Chart performance and sales===\nIn the week of its release, ''New Surrender'' sold 36,000 units, entering the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at the number 13 position, surpassing the number 19 peak reached by ''[[Cities (Anberlin album)|Cities]]''.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043841/ti-debuts-big-atop-billboard-200-hot-100|title=T.I. Debuts Big Atop Billboard 200, Hot 100|publisher=Billboard|last=Hasty|first=Katie|date=October 8, 2008|accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref> It was also announced that the album had debuted at number five on the Billboard Top Modern Rock / Alternative Albums chart,<ref name=\"MarketWatch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/anberlin-debuts-13-billboard-top/story.aspx?guid={14845DC7-8BDD-4472-A3AA-F57D801E8253}&dist=hppr|title=Anberlin Debuts at #13 on Billboard Top 200 and #5 on Top Current Rock Chart with New Surrender|publisher=MarketWatch|date=October 8, 2008|accessdate=October 8, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-11-01/alternative-albums |title=Top Modern Rock/Alternative Albums - Anberlin New Surrender |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=October 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150105005714/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-11-01/alternative-albums |archivedate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref> number one on the Top Christian Albums chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/news/New_Hit/34135/p1/|title=Anberlin storm US charts with new album|publisher=Cross Rhythms|accessdate=October 28, 2008}}</ref> number six on the Top Digital Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-10-25/digital-albums |title=Top Digital Albums - Anberlin New Surrender |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=October 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150105153146/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-10-25/digital-albums |archivedate=January 5, 2015 }}</ref> ''New Surrender'' came in at number 85 on the Australian [[ARIA charts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/chartifacts.htm|title=ARIA Chartifacts|publisher=ARIAcharts|accessdate=October 18, 2008|archivedate=October 13, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013194936/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/chartifacts.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn its first two weeks, ''New Surrender'' sold over 45,000 copies in the [[United States]] alone.<ref name=\"NewSurrendersales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=616892|title=Anberlin's Second Week|publisher=Absolutepunk.net|last=Tate|first=Jason|date=October 15, 2008|accessdate=October 20, 2008}}</ref> The album held its ground in the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], staying in the top 100 for three weeks, coming in at number 50 in week two and 79 in week three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-11-01/billboard-200 |title=The Billboard 200 - Anberlin New Surrender |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=October 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104130253/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-11-01/billboard-200 |archivedate=January 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n====Singles chart positions====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"110\"|Single\n! width=\"220\"|Chart (2009)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[Feel Good Drag]]\"\n|{{nowrap|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Modern Rock Tracks]]}}<ref name=hotmod>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=anberlin|chart=all}}|title=Artist Chart History - Anberlin singles|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=December 11, 2008}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 1\n|-\n|{{nowrap|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=anberlin|chart=Bubbling Under Hot 100}}|title=Bubbling Under Hot 100 - Feel Good Drag |work=Billboard|accessdate=March 27, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n*All songs written and composed by [[Anberlin]] unless otherwise noted.\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        =\n| title1          = The Resistance\n| writer1         = Christian; Milligan; Anberlin\n| length1         = 3:17\n| title2          = [[Breaking (Anberlin Song)|Breaking]]\n| writer2         = Christian; Milligan; [[Butch Walker|Walker]]; Anberlin\n| length2         = 3:26\n| title3          = Blame Me! Blame Me!\n| writer3         = Christian; Milligan; Anberlin\n| length3         = 3:09\n| title4          = Retrace\n| writer4         = Christian; McAlhaney; Milligan; [[Dan Wilson (musician)|Wilson]]; Anberlin\n| length4         = 3:51\n| title5          = [[Feel Good Drag]]\n| writer5         = Christian; Milligan; Anberlin\n| length5         = 3:08\n| title6          = Disappear\n| writer6         = Christian; Milligan; McAlhaney; Anberlin\n| length6         = 3:37\n| title7        