t\n*Kyle Griner - management\n*[[Ted Jensen]] - mastering\n*Mike Laza - assistant engineer\n*Tom MacKay - A&R\n*James Minchin - photography\n*Alyssa Pittaluga - assistant engineer\n*Erich Talaba - engineer\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n;General\n* {{cite AV media notes|title = New Surrender|others = [[Anberlin]]|year = 2008|type = CD|publisher = [[Universal Motown Republic Group|Universal Republic]]|id = B0011710-02}}\n;Specific\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Anberlin}}\n\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n[[Category:Anberlin albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Neal Avron]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Mike Fasano", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Surrender"}
{"title_page": "New Maps of Hell (Bad Religion album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = New Maps of Hell\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Bad Religion]]\n| cover      = Bad Religion - New Maps of Hell.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2007|7|10}}\n| recorded   = February\u2013April 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Grandmaster Records, Ltd. in Hollywood\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]], [[melodic hardcore]]\n| length     = 38:27\n| label      = [[Epitaph Records|Epitaph]]\n| producer   = [[Joe Barresi]]\n| prev_title = [[The Empire Strikes First]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[30 Years Live]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = New Maps of Hell\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Honest Goodbye\n | single1date = May 22, 2007\n | single2     = New Dark Ages\n | single2date = October 23, 2007\n}}\n}}\n'''''New Maps of Hell''''' is the fourteenth studio album by [[Bad Religion]], released on July 10, 2007.\n\nBad Religion's follow-up to 2004's ''[[The Empire Strikes First]]'' was originally rumored to be a double album to be released in 2006, but this was denied by bassist [[Jay Bentley]]. Due to the band's ongoing support with their previous release, the album was put on hold until 2007. Another one of the reasons why the band had yet to release a follow-up to ''The Empire Strikes First'' was their various other activities, most obviously frontman [[Greg Graffin]]'s, who released his [[Cold as the Clay|second solo album]] in 2006, his first since [[American Lesion|1997]].\n\n''New Maps of Hell'' also marks the third Bad Religion album released after returning to [[Epitaph Records]] for 2002's ''[[The Process of Belief]]'' and with Gurewitz since his departure during the release of 1994's ''[[Stranger than Fiction (Bad Religion album)|Stranger Than Fiction]]''.\n\n==Background and composition==\nBad Religion first mentioned the follow-up to ''[[The Empire Strikes First]]'' in 2005, stating that the band would begin recording it later that year, making it likely that it would be released sometime in 2006.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=777 New album \"sometime in 2006\"], The Bad Religion Page, May 5, 2005</ref> In July 2005, it was announced that Graffin and Gurewitz had begun writing \"about 20 songs or more\" for the album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=818 Bad Religion Come Back?], The Bad Religion Page, July 18, 2005</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2006, it was announced that Bad Religion was \"almost 100% ready to go back to the studio or to the house\" to begin working on the album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=951 Back to the studio soon?], The Bad Religion Page, January 20, 2006</ref> Members of the band had mentioned that it would be a double release,<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=995 Double Disc!], The Bad Religion Page, March 14, 2006</ref> but this idea was later turned down flat by Bentley.<ref>[http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/bad_religion_bassist_talks_on_new_album_upcoming_tour.html Bad Religion Bassist Talks On New Album, Upcoming Tour], [[Ultimate Guitar Archive|Ultimate-Guitar.com]], March 1, 2007</ref>\n\nIn early February 2006, Bentley was chatting with a visitor who comments on news articles at the official Bad Religion fansite, stating that the new Bad Religion album was planned for a September release, as well as a tour to follow.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=964 New album out in September], The Bad Religion Page, February 2, 2006</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nIn May 2006, Bentley also mentioned that the band was planning to begin recording it around late June/early July.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=1024 Bad Religion Podcast], The Bad Religion Page, May 4, 2006</ref> In September, the band mentioned they were in the process of demoing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1255|title=Bad Religion working on new album for 2007 release|work=Alternative Press|date=September 13, 2006|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBentley also told Kristoffer Averheim, the webmaster of the Bad Religion fansite, that the album had been pushed back to late 2006/early 2007.<ref>[http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/bad_religion_new_album_update.html Bad Religion: New Album Update], [[Ultimate Guitar Archive|Ultimate-Guitar.com]], June 27, 2006</ref> While drummer [[Brooks Wackerman]] posted a message on MySpace stating that the band had continued working on a new album, he stated that the album was once again pushed back to \"mid/late 2007\".\n\nIn January 2007, it was announced that the album would be called ''New Maps of Hell'' and would work with producer [[Joe Barresi]].<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/21802 Bad Religion confirms July 10th release date], Punknews.org, January 18, 2007</ref> The band began recording at Grand Master Studios in Los Angeles, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1697|title=Bad Religion set studio time, release date for new album|work=Alternative Press|date=January 18, 2007|accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> On April 1, Bentley posted an update on the MySpace bulletin board, stating that the band was finally finished recording the album and would soon begin mixing it.<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/23041 Bad Religion finish recording \"New Maps of Hell\"], Punknews.org, April 2, 2007</ref> He had this to say:\n\n:{{cquote|We are done recording. Now it's mix time. We're getting ready to play the Santa Monica show and head down to Chile, Argentina, Brazil and Mexico for our tour... looking forward to getting back on the road...}}\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2007, ''New Maps of Hell'' was announced for release and the track listing was revealed.<ref name=AltPannounce>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1875|title=Bad Religion reveal album details|work=Alternative Press|date=March 16, 2007|accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref> The song \"Heroes and Martyrs\" was introduced to the public on April 6 at the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium during an encore as a small preview of \"New Maps of Hell\". On April 25, the track listing was rearranged and the track \"New Chapter\" was dropped.<ref>[http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516/], Epitaph.com, April 25, 2007</ref> When asked why \"New Chapter\" would not appear on the album, Bentley recently stated that it \"ran into insurmountable issues\" that the band \"couldn't rectify\", hinting that it will probably appear on the next Bad Religion album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=1290 New Chapter], The Bad Religion Page, April 28, 2007</ref> \"Honest Goodbye\" was made available for streaming via the band's [[Myspace]] account on May 15,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2053|title=Bad Religion post first single from New Maps Of Hell|work=Alternative Press|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> and released as a single a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2032|title=Bad Religion to release digital single on May 22|work=Alternative Press|date=May 8, 2007|accessdate=August 12, 2016}}</ref> On May 25, \"Heroes & Martyrs\" was released as a free download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2097|title=Bad Religion post new song from New Maps Of Hell|work=Alternative Press|date=May 25, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Honest Goodbye\" was released to radio on June 12, 2007.<ref name=FMQB>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771|title=FMQB Airplay Archive: Modern Rock|publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Incorporated|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> From late June to late August, the band went on the 2007 edition of [[Warped Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1997|title=Throwdown added to Warped 07; Madina Lake drop off|work=Alternative Press|date=April 26, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref> ''New Maps of Hell'' was made available for streaming on July 3,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2234|title=Bad Religion stream new album on MySpace|work=Alternative Press|date=July 3, 2007|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> and released a week later through Epitaph.<ref name=AltPannounce/> Discussing the album's title, guitarist [[Brett Gurewitz]] stated \"We all liked the concept of maps, because we are exploring new material on this record, both musically and topically.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516 |title=Epitaph Records: Bad Religion \u2013 New Maps of Hell |publisher=Epitaph.com |accessdate=2011-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120203121/http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516/ |archivedate=November 20, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In September and October, the band went on a headlining tour across the US, with support from [[the Briggs]] and [[Gallows (band)|Gallows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2528|title=Bad Religion line up fall tour with the Briggs, Gallows|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 20, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref> \"New Dark Ages\" was released to radio on October 23.<ref name=\"FMQB\" /> On November 14, a music video was released for \"New Dark Ages\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3011|title=Bad Religion premiere \"New Dark Ages\" video|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=November 14, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> The video for \"Honest Goodbye\" was planned, but \"never made it out of the office\" according to Bentley. \n\nOn February 27, 2008, Punknews.org reported that Epitaph would be releasing a deluxe edition of New Maps of Hell on July 8.<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/27896 NMoH Deluxe Edition], PunkNews.org, February 27, 2008</ref> In February and March, the band went on a west coast tour of the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3350|title=Bad Religion playing a handful of California/Vegas dates|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=January 16, 2008|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> On May 9, 2008, Punknews.org released the artwork for the reissue and more details, including the track list and the bonus DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punknews.org/article/28823 |title=Bad Religion post new \"New Maps of Hell\" artwork |publisher=Punknews.org |date= |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref> It contains two double-sided posters. The DVD features an hour of a live performance, music videos for \"New Dark Ages\" and \"Honest Goodbye\", a showing of Bad Religion making New Maps of Hell and Graffin and Gurewitz recording the acoustic bonus tracks. It also has seven bonus tracks which are performed acoustically. An acoustic version of \"Sorrow\" was posted on the band's Myspace on July 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_4219|title=Bad Religion posts song from \u2018New Maps Of Hell\u2019 deluxe|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> Between late June and late August 2008, the band performed on the [[Warped Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/32844/tours-warped-tour-2009|title=Warped Tour 2009|work=Punknews.org|publisher=Aubin Paul|author=Paul, Aubin|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> In September and October, the band went on a tour of Australia with [[NOFX]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_6523|title=Bad Religion / NOFX heading down under|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=April 16, 2009|accessdate=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 69/100 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/new-maps-of-hell/bad-religion|title=New Maps of Hell by Bad Religion|publisher=|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r1081034|pure_url=yes}} |title=AllMusic review}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/bad-religion-emnew-maps-of-hellem-7693|title=Bad Religion: New Maps Of Hell|date=July 17, 2007|publisher=|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3      = [[IGN]]\n| rev3Score = 8.7/10 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/812/812219p1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214161734/http://music.ign.com/articles/812/812219p1.html|title=Bad Religion - New Maps of Hell|publisher=IGN|author=Thompson, Ed|date=August 10, 2007|archivedate=February 14, 2012|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}\n| rev5 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/46752/bad-religion-new-maps-of-hell/ |title=PopMatters review}}</ref>\n| rev6 = Punknews.org\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punknews.org/review/6479 |title=Punknews.org review}}</ref>\n}}\nFollowing the album's release, it debuted at number 35 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling about 21,000 copies in its first week.<ref>Katie Hasty, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1050782/ti-holds-off-pumpkins-interpol-to-remain-no-1 \"T.I. Holds Off Pumpkins, Interpol To Remain No. 1\"], Billboard.com, July 18, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| title1          = 52 Seconds\n| writer1         = [[Brett Gurewitz]]\n| length1         = 0:58\n| title2          = Heroes & Martyrs\n| writer2         = Gurewitz\n| length2         = 1:25\n| title3          = Germs of Perfection\n| writer3         = [[Greg Graffin]]\n| length3         = 1:27\n| title4          = New Dark Ages\n| writer4         = Gurewitz\n| length4         = 2:47\n| title5          = Requiem for Dissent\n| writer5         = Graffin\n| length5         = 2:08\n| title6          = Before You Die\n| writer6         = Graffin\n| length6         = 2:34\n| title7          = Honest Goodbye\n| writer7         = Gurewitz\n| length7         = 2:51\n| title8          = Dearly Beloved\n| writer8         = Gurewitz\n| length8         = 2:19\n| title9          = Grains of Wrath\n| writer9         = Graffin\n| length9         = 3:00\n| title10         = Murder\n| writer10        = Gurewitz\n| length10        = 1:18\n| title11         = Scrutiny\n| writer11        = Graffin\n| length11        = 2:36\n| title12         = Prodigal Son\n| writer12        = Gurewitz\n| length12        = 3:07\n| title13         = The Grand Delusion\n| writer13        = Graffin\n| length13        = 2:10\n| title14         = Lost Pilgrim\n| writer14        = Graffin\n| length14        = 2:28\n| title15         = Submission Complete\n| writer15        = Graffin\n| length15        = 3:40\n| title16         = Fields of Mars\n| writer16        = Gurewitz\n| length16        = 3:39\n|total_length = 38:27\n}}\n\n;Deluxe edition bonus tracks\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Deluxe edition\n| collapsed = yes\n| title17         = \n| writer17        = \n| length17        = 0:04\n| title18         = Won't Somebody\n| writer18        = Gurewitz\n| note18          = acoustic\n| length18        = 3:08\n| title19         = Adam's Atoms\n| writer19        = Graffin\n| note19          = acoustic\n| length19        = 2:37\n| title20         = [[Sorrow (Bad Religion song)|Sorrow]]\n| writer20        = Gurewitz\n| note20          = acoustic\n| length20        = 3:12\n| title21         = God Song\n| writer21        = Graffin\n| note21          = acoustic\n| length21        = 2:40\n| title22         = Dearly Beloved\n| writer22        = Gurewitz\n| note22          = acoustic\n| length22        = 2:37\n| title23         = Chronophobia\n| writer23        = Graffin\n| note23          = acoustic\n| length23        = 1:55\n| title24         = Skyscraper\n| writer24        = Gurewitz\n| note24          = acoustic\n| length24        = 3:00\n|total_length = 60:19\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Greg Graffin]] \u2013 vocals, piano\n* [[Brett Gurewitz]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Brian Baker (musician)|Brian Baker]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Greg Hetson]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Jay Bentley]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* [[Brooks Wackerman]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Joe Barresi]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Mike Fasano (musician)|Mike Fasano]] \u2013 drum technician\n* Andrew Alekel \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Nick Pritchard \u2013 art direction, design\n* Bryan Sheffield \u2013 photography\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLtKArKK2vi6QUl0jyan4WLG7F3mnp3Nrj ''New Maps of Hell''] at YouTube (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n{{Bad Religion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Maps Of Hell}}\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Joe Barresi]]\n[[Category:Bad Religion albums]]\n[[Category:Epitaph Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = New Maps of Hell\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Bad Religion]]\n| cover      = Bad Religion - New Maps of Hell.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2007|7|10}}\n| recorded   = February\u2013April 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Grandmaster Records, Ltd. in Hollywood\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]], [[melodic hardcore]]\n| length     = 38:27\n| label      = [[Epitaph Records|Epitaph]]\n| producer   = [[Joe Barresi]]\n| prev_title = [[The Empire Strikes First]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[30 Years Live]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = New Maps of Hell\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Honest Goodbye\n | single1date = May 22, 2007\n | single2     = New Dark Ages\n | single2date = October 23, 2007\n}}\n}}\n'''''New Maps of Hell''''' is the fourteenth studio album by [[Bad Religion]], released on July 10, 2007.\n\nBad Religion's follow-up to 2004's ''[[The Empire Strikes First]]'' was originally rumored to be a double album to be released in 2006, but this was denied by bassist [[Jay Bentley]]. Due to the band's ongoing support with their previous release, the album was put on hold until 2007. Another one of the reasons why the band had yet to release a follow-up to ''The Empire Strikes First'' was their various other activities, most obviously frontman [[Greg Graffin]]'s, who released his [[Cold as the Clay|second solo album]] in 2006, his first since [[American Lesion|1997]].\n\n''New Maps of Hell'' also marks the third Bad Religion album released after returning to [[Epitaph Records]] for 2002's ''[[The Process of Belief]]'' and with Gurewitz since his departure during the release of 1994's ''[[Stranger than Fiction (Bad Religion album)|Stranger Than Fiction]].\n\n==Background and composition==\nBad Religion first mentioned the follow-up to ''[[The Empire Strikes First]]'' in 2005, stating that the band would begin recording it later that year, making it likely that it would be released sometime in 2006.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=777 New album \"sometime in 2006\"], The Bad Religion Page, May 5, 2005</ref> In July 2005, it was announced that Graffin and Gurewitz had begun writing \"about 20 songs or more\" for the album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=818 Bad Religion Come Back?], The Bad Religion Page, July 18, 2005</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2006, it was announced that Bad Religion was \"almost 100% ready to go back to the studio or to the house\" to begin working on the album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=951 Back to the studio soon?], The Bad Religion Page, January 20, 2006</ref> Members of the band had mentioned that it would be a double release,<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=995 Double Disc!], The Bad Religion Page, March 14, 2006</ref> but this idea was later turned down flat by Bentley.<ref>[http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/bad_religion_bassist_talks_on_new_album_upcoming_tour.html Bad Religion Bassist Talks On New Album, Upcoming Tour], [[Ultimate Guitar Archive|Ultimate-Guitar.com]], March 1, 2007</ref>\n\nIn early February 2006, Bentley was chatting with a visitor who comments on news articles at the official Bad Religion fansite, stating that the new Bad Religion album was planned for a September release, as well as a tour to follow.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=964 New album out in September], The Bad Religion Page, February 2, 2006</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nIn May 2006, Bentley also mentioned that the band was planning to begin recording it around late June/early July.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=1024 Bad Religion Podcast], The Bad Religion Page, May 4, 2006</ref> In September, the band mentioned they were in the process of demoing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1255|title=Bad Religion working on new album for 2007 release|work=Alternative Press|date=September 13, 2006|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBentley also told Kristoffer Averheim, the webmaster of the Bad Religion fansite, that the album had been pushed back to late 2006/early 2007.<ref>[http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/bad_religion_new_album_update.html Bad Religion: New Album Update], [[Ultimate Guitar Archive|Ultimate-Guitar.com]], June 27, 2006</ref> While drummer [[Brooks Wackerman]] posted a message on MySpace stating that the band had continued working on a new album, he stated that the album was once again pushed back to \"mid/late 2007\".\n\nIn January 2007, it was announced that the album would be called ''New Maps of Hell'' and would work with producer [[Joe Barresi]].<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/21802 Bad Religion confirms July 10th release date], Punknews.org, January 18, 2007</ref> The band began recording at Grand Master Studios in Los Angeles, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1697|title=Bad Religion set studio time, release date for new album|work=Alternative Press|date=January 18, 2007|accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> On April 1, Bentley posted an update on the MySpace bulletin board, stating that the band was finally finished recording the album and would soon begin mixing it.<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/23041 Bad Religion finish recording \"New Maps of Hell\"], Punknews.org, April 2, 2007</ref> He had this to say:\n\n:{{cquote|We are done recording. Now it's mix time. We're getting ready to play the Santa Monica show and head down to Chile, Argentina, Brazil and Mexico for our tour... looking forward to getting back on the road...}}\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2007, ''New Maps of Hell'' was announced for release and the track listing was revealed.<ref name=AltPannounce>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1875|title=Bad Religion reveal album details|work=Alternative Press|date=March 16, 2007|accessdate=August 10, 2016}}</ref> The song \"Heroes and Martyrs\" was introduced to the public on April 6 at the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium during an encore as a small preview of \"New Maps of Hell\". On April 25, the track listing was rearranged and the track \"New Chapter\" was dropped.<ref>[http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516/], Epitaph.com, April 25, 2007</ref> When asked why \"New Chapter\" would not appear on the album, Bentley recently stated that it \"ran into insurmountable issues\" that the band \"couldn't rectify\", hinting that it will probably appear on the next Bad Religion album.<ref>[http://www.thebrpage.net/news/news_item.asp?NewsID=1290 New Chapter], The Bad Religion Page, April 28, 2007</ref> \"Honest Goodbye\" was made available for streaming via the band's [[Myspace]] account on May 15,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2053|title=Bad Religion post first single from New Maps Of Hell|work=Alternative Press|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> and released as a single a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2032|title=Bad Religion to release digital single on May 22|work=Alternative Press|date=May 8, 2007|accessdate=August 12, 2016}}</ref> On May 25, \"Heroes & Martyrs\" was released as a free download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2097|title=Bad Religion post new song from New Maps Of Hell|work=Alternative Press|date=May 25, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Honest Goodbye\" was released to radio on June 12, 2007.<ref name=FMQB>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771|title=FMQB Airplay Archive: Modern Rock|publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Incorporated|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> From late June to late August, the band went on the 2007 edition of [[Warped Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_1997|title=Throwdown added to Warped 07; Madina Lake drop off|work=Alternative Press|date=April 26, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref> ''New Maps of Hell'' was made available for streaming on July 3,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2234|title=Bad Religion stream new album on MySpace|work=Alternative Press|date=July 3, 2007|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> and released a week later through Epitaph.<ref name=AltPannounce/> Discussing the album's title, guitarist [[Brett Gurewitz]] stated \"We all liked the concept of maps, because we are exploring new material on this record, both musically and topically.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516 |title=Epitaph Records: Bad Religion \u2013 New Maps of Hell |publisher=Epitaph.com |accessdate=2011-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120203121/http://www.epitaph.com/artists/album/516/ |archivedate=November 20, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In September and October, the band went on a headlining tour across the US, with support from [[the Briggs]] and [[Gallows (band)|Gallows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2528|title=Bad Religion line up fall tour with the Briggs, Gallows|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 20, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref> \"New Dark Ages\" was released to radio on October 23.<ref name=\"FMQB\" /> On November 14, a music video was released for \"New Dark Ages\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3011|title=Bad Religion premiere \"New Dark Ages\" video|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=November 14, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> The video for \"Honest Goodbye\" was planned, but \"never made it out of the office\" according to Bentley. \n\nOn February 27, 2008, Punknews.org reported that Epitaph would be releasing a deluxe edition of New Maps of Hell on July 8.<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/article/27896 NMoH Deluxe Edition], PunkNews.org, February 27, 2008</ref> In February and March, the band went on a west coast tour of the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3350|title=Bad Religion playing a handful of California/Vegas dates|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=January 16, 2008|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> On May 9, 2008, Punknews.org released the artwork for the reissue and more details, including the track list and the bonus DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punknews.org/article/28823 |title=Bad Religion post new \"New Maps of Hell\" artwork |publisher=Punknews.org |date= |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref> It contains two double-sided posters. The DVD features an hour of a live performance, music videos for \"New Dark Ages\" and \"Honest Goodbye\", a showing of Bad Religion making New Maps of Hell and Graffin and Gurewitz recording the acoustic bonus tracks. It also has seven bonus tracks which are performed acoustically. An acoustic version of \"Sorrow\" was posted on the band's Myspace on July 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_4219|title=Bad Religion posts song from \u2018New Maps Of Hell\u2019 deluxe|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> Between late June and late August 2008, the band performed on the [[Warped Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/32844/tours-warped-tour-2009|title=Warped Tour 2009|work=Punknews.org|publisher=Aubin Paul|author=Paul, Aubin|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> In September and October, the band went on a tour of Australia with [[NOFX]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_6523|title=Bad Religion / NOFX heading down under|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=April 16, 2009|accessdate=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 69/100 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/new-maps-of-hell/bad-religion|title=New Maps of Hell by Bad Religion|publisher=|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r1081034|pure_url=yes}} |title=AllMusic review}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/bad-religion-emnew-maps-of-hellem-7693|title=Bad Religion: New Maps Of Hell|date=July 17, 2007|publisher=|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3      = [[IGN]]\n| rev3Score = 8.7/10 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/812/812219p1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214161734/http://music.ign.com/articles/812/812219p1.html|title=Bad Religion - New Maps of Hell|publisher=IGN|author=Thompson, Ed|date=August 10, 2007|archivedate=February 14, 2012|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}\n| rev5 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/46752/bad-religion-new-maps-of-hell/ |title=PopMatters review}}</ref>\n| rev6 = Punknews.org\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punknews.org/review/6479 |title=Punknews.org review}}</ref>\n}}\nFollowing the album's release, it debuted at number 35 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling about 21,000 copies in its first week.<ref>Katie Hasty, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1050782/ti-holds-off-pumpkins-interpol-to-remain-no-1 \"T.I. Holds Off Pumpkins, Interpol To Remain No. 1\"], Billboard.com, July 18, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| title1          = 52 Seconds\n| writer1         = [[Brett Gurewitz]]\n| length1         = 0:58\n| title2          = Heroes & Martyrs\n| writer2         = Gurewitz\n| length2         = 1:25\n| title3          = Germs of Perfection\n| writer3         = [[Greg Graffin]]\n| length3         = 1:27\n| title4          = New Dark Ages\n| writer4         = Gurewitz\n| length4         = 2:47\n| title5          = Requiem for Dissent\n| writer5         = Graffin\n| length5         = 2:08\n| title6          = Before You Die\n|