24        = 3:00\n|total_length = 60:19\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Greg Graffin]] \u2013 vocals, piano\n* [[Brett Gurewitz]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Brian Baker (musician)|Brian Baker]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Greg Hetson]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Jay Bentley]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* [[Brooks Wackerman]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Joe Barresi]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Mike Fasano]] \u2013 drum technician\n* Andrew Alekel \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Nick Pritchard \u2013 art direction, design\n* Bryan Sheffield \u2013 photography\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLtKArKK2vi6QUl0jyan4WLG7F3mnp3Nrj ''New Maps of Hell''] at YouTube (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n{{Bad Religion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Maps Of Hell}}\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Joe Barresi]]\n[[Category:Bad Religion albums]]\n[[Category:Epitaph Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Mike Fasano/WP:WCWproject (Missing end bold/italic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Maps_of_Hell_(Bad_Religion_album)"}
{"title_page": "Cleber Machado Neto - Sculptor", "text_new": "{{Prod blp/dated\n  |concern = \n  |user = \n  |timestamp = 20200422145643\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{edit request}}\n\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Cleber Machado\n| image            = Cleber Machado Neto.jpg\n| caption          = Retrato de Cleber para exposi\u00e7\u00e3o de [[Eddy Novarro]], abril de 1988\n| birth_name       = Cleber Machado Neto \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1937|6|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Porto Alegre]], Brazil\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| nationality      = Brazilian\n| education        = \n| known_for        = sculpture\n| notable_works    = {{unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Arte Contempor\u00e2nea Brasileira - Bankboston]]'' (1970)\n  | ''[[Pesquisa Joia - XI Bienal Internacional de S\u00e3o Paulo, Brasil)]]'' (1971)\n  | ''[[Pesquisa - I Bienal Nacional S\u00e3o Paulo, Brasil]]'' (1972)\n  | ''[[Especial Escultura - II Bienal Internacional Makurazaki, Jap\u00e3o]]'' (1991)\n  }}\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n}}\n\n'''Cleber Machado''' ([[June]] 25th, [[1937]], [[Porto Alegre]]) is a [[Brazilian]] [[artist]], [[sculptor]] and [[painter]]. Today he lives and works in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. Exhibits individually since [[1971]] and in group since [[1968]]. The artist's [[literature]] includes texts by leading critics. He received several national and international awards and his work is part of important public and private collections.\nSon of Marina Machado Neto e Jo\u00e3o Pedro Pereira Neto, in [[1960]], Cleber moves with the family to [[Rio de Janeiro]], where he joins the student movement, alongside of his friends and also artists of the School of Fine Arts of Rio, [[Artur Barrio]] and [[Rubens Gerchman]]. \nIn [[1968]], amid demonstrations and the National Salon of [[Modern Art]], he is arrested and released within 24 hours - influenced by his father\u00b4s friend. The fright took him away from street demonstrations, but did not take his political interest and engagement. \nPrior to expressing himself as a sculptor, while living in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santa_Teresa_(bairro_do_Rio_de_Janeiro) Santa Tereza], Cleber began designing and producing [[jewelry]] in [[silver]] and [[acrylic]]. This excursion earned him the Jewelry Research award of the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo]. Years later, he resumes jewelry production, this time strongly influenced by [[sculpture]], with the creation of the Sculpture to Wear Collection, composed of true sculptures to be worn on fingers as rings.\nBetween [[1970]] and [[1974]], he had a studio in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Botafogo Botafogo], where he taught several courses and, at the invitation of the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo], participated in the [[Bras\u00edlia]] Room, where his work was acquired by the President [[Juscelino Kubitschek]] to compose the collection of the future [[Brazilian]] Art Museum, built in the federal capital. \nAfter a visit to [[Guaratiba]], a beach 40 kilometers from Rio, where he resumed an old passion for submarine hunting, he moves to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] and performs an exhibition on the shores of [[Ibirapuera Park]] Lake with [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Museu_de_Arte_Moderna_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo MAM-SP]. From [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] he embarks for a period in [[New York City]] and next settles for three years in [[Mexico City]] where he presents his installation \"Archeology of the Year 4000\" (according to him, a great responsibility, since his work was exhibited shortly after the closing of [[Henry Moore]]\u00b4s exhibition.\nBack to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], Cleber builds a studio in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A3o_Crist%C3%B3v%C3%A3o_(bairro_do_Rio_de_Janeiro) S\u00e3o Critov\u00e3o] where he works for the next two years. His participation at the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo 20th International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo] is highlighted by \u201cEarth, Water and Air\u201d performance, where a helicopter simulates the presence and landing of a UFO in [[Ibirapuera Park]] lake. In early 90s, moves back to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] and, once recovered of a period of depression, resumes vigorously his original language, as he likes to call it, \u201coneiric geometry\u201d. His comeback is highlighted by an exposition in the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casa_das_Rosas House of Roses Garden] (currently [[Haroldo de Campos]] Poetry Space).\n\n== Individual Expositions ==\n\n[[File:Cleber Machado - Miragem I, II e III, 1988.JPG|thumb|border|280px|left|Cleber Machado - Miragem I, II e III, 1988]]\n\n*1971 - Rio de Janeiro Art Museum - MAM Rio\n*1980 \u2013 S\u00e3o Paulo Modern Art Museum - MASP\n*1983 - Museo de Arte Moderno - M\u00e9xico\n*1984 - Rio de Janeiro Art Museum- MAM Rio\n*1997/98 \u2013 House of Roses - S\u00e3o Paulo\n*1999 - Ricardo Camargo Gallery - S\u00e3o Paulo\n*2000 \u2013 The Greenhouse - S\u00e3o Paulo\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Collective Expositions ==\n[[File:Niomar Moniz Sodr\u00e9 Bittencourt.jpg|thumb|border|350px| Cleber Machado and Niomar Moniz Sodr\u00e9 Bittencourt]]\n\n*1968 a 1971 - National Salon of Modern Art - Brazil\n*1970 - BankBoston - Brazilian Contemporary Art - Rio de Janeiro - Brazil\n*1970 - Pre-Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brasil\n*1971 - XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1971 \u2013 Pan American Festival of Culture - Cali - Colombia\n*1972 - Brazil Plastic 72 - Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brasil\n*1972 - 1991 - Brazilian Sculpture Overview - MAM - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1975 - XIII International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1979 - XV International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1979 - Alternative Space \"Galp\u00e3o\"- S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1982 \u2013 12th International Sculpture Conference - San Francisco - EUA\n*1982 - 100 Years of Brazilian Sculpture - MASP - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1987 - Brazilian Contemporary Art - Trends - Rio de Janeiro - Brasil\n*1989 - XX International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Special Events, S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1991 - Montesanti Gallery, International Art Fair, Bogot\u00e1 - Colombia\n*1991 - International Biennial of Makurazaki - Japan\n*1996 - Brazilian Museum of Sculpture - Sao Paulo - Brazil\n*1998 - Campinas Contemporary Art Museum - Master's Touch - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n\n== New York Project==\n<gallery>\nFile:ProjectoOctopus2.jpg|\nFile:ProjetoOctopus1.jpg|\nFile:Machado3ny.jpg|\n</gallery>\n'''Octopus'''<br>\n\nAs [[Pierre Restany]] said, Cleber's [[art critic]] and personal friend, in a written text by him in [[1982]], \u201c... Machado is indeed a message bearer. He conceived a whole program of interventions, from which \u201cOctopus\u201d is the starting point to give his art the existential span of a vital phenomenon. Look into [[New York City]] sky the evolution of a giant octopus. What will be the reaction of people around a corner? Imagination takes power among the skyscrapers of [[Wall Street]], caresses the [[Statue of Liberty]]. More than art in freedom, Machado tries to grab our interest in our essential freedom of being. His dream, if we share it, is a call to order, to existential order, to the law of the great nature.\u201d\n\n== S\u00e3o Paulo Project ==\n<gallery>\nFile:20_Bienal_Internacional_de_S\u00e3o_Paulo.jpg|[http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 20a Bienal Internacional de S\u00e3o Paulo]\nFile:Disco_-_1989.jpg| [http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 Projeto S\u00e3o Paulo - 1989],p.77\nFile:\" Um sonho e uma chamda a ordem\".jpg| [http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 Projeto S\u00e3o Paulo - 1989],p.77\nFile:Cleber_e_Pierre.jpg|[[Pierre Restany]]\n</gallery>\n\n'''An UFO in S\u00e3o Paulo'''<br>\n\nTo be presented in the Special Events of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo#20%C2%AA_Bienal_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo_(1989) 20th International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo] ([[1989]]), Cleber Machado prepares an urban interference from outer world. From [[Congonhas Airport]]  (SP), a helicopter disguised as an UFO takes off, equipped with 20 green and blue light beams. The \"disk\" flies over the city for about 40 minutes, describing symmetrical routes and spiraling down over the [[Ibirapuera Park]] lake. According to Cleber, the purpose of this interference is to enable a dive of fantasy into reality, provoking individuals, stimulating them into new sensations or a new perception of reality.\n\n== Selected Collections == \n[[File:Esfera..jpg|thumb|border|240px|right|Esfera.]]\n\n*Rio de Janeiro Modern Art Museum - MAM Rio\n*S\u00e3o Paulo Modern Art Museum - MAM SP\n*Museo de Arte Moderno - M\u00e9xico\n*Brazilian Art Museum from Armando \u00c1lvares Penteado Foundation - MAB FAAP - SP\n*Museo Rayo - Roldenibe Del Vale - Colombia\n*Brazilian Art Museum - Bras\u00edlia - Brasil\n*Latin American Art Center - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Museo de Arte Americano - Man\u00e1gua - Nicar\u00e1gua\n*Stado of S\u00e3o Paulo Archive - Brasil\n*Museo de Arte Moderna - La Tertulia - Cali - Col\u00f4mbia\n*Museo Casa Del Lago - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Nanmeikan Modern Art - Makurazaki - Jap\u00e3o\n*Museo El Chopo - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Londrina Art Museum - Paran\u00e1 - Brasil\n\n== Awards ==\n[[File:Cleber Machado - \u00c1rvore, 1991.JPG|thumb|border|240px|right|Cleber Machado - \u00c1rvore, 1991]]\n\n*1970 Brazilian Contemporary Art - Bankboston  \n*1971 Jewelry Research - XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil  \n*1972 Research - I National Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil  \n*1991 Special Sculpture - II International Biennial of Makurazaki, Japan\n\n== External Links ==\n[[File:Desenho de Cleber por Julio Larraz.jpg|thumb|border|250px|left|Desenho de Cleber por Julio Larraz]]\n\n\n*[http://www.art-bonobo.com/artes/clebermachado/welcome.html Art Bonobo]\n*[http://www.bolsadearte.com/artistas/perfil/id/399/ Bolsa de Arte]\n*[http://www.espacoarte.com.br/artistas/cleber-machado?id=518# Galeria Espa\u00e7o Arte]\n*[http://mam.org.br/visite/jardim-de-esculturas/ MAM - Jardins das Esculturas]\n*[http://www.rcamargoarte.com.br/expo/?expo=65 Ricardo Camargo Galeria]\n*[http://enciclopedia.itaucultural.org.br/pessoa26332/cleber-machado/Enciclop\u00e9dia Ita\u00fa Cultural]\n*[https://oscardambrosio.com.br/artistas/399/cleber-machado/Oscar D'Ambrosio]\n*[https://mam.org.br/en/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2014/06/MitologiasDEF.pdf/Mitologias MAM-SP]\n", "text_old": "{{Prod blp/dated\n  |concern = \n  |user = \n  |timestamp = 20200422145643\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{edit request}}\n\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Cleber Machado\n| image            = Cleber Machado Neto.jpg\n| caption          = Retrato de Cleber para exposi\u00e7\u00e3o de [[Eddy Novarro]], abril de 1988\n| birth_name       = Cleber Machado Neto \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1937|6|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Porto Alegre]], Brazil\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| nationality      = Brazilian\n| education        = \n| known_for        = sculpture\n| notable_works    = {{unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Arte Contempor\u00e2nea Brasileira - Bankboston]]'' (1970)\n  | ''[[Pesquisa Joia - XI Bienal Internacional de S\u00e3o Paulo, Brasil)]]'' (1971)\n  | ''[[Pesquisa - I Bienal Nacional S\u00e3o Paulo, Brasil]]'' (1972)\n  | ''[[Especial Escultura - II Bienal Internacional Makurazaki, Jap\u00e3o]]'' (1991)\n  }}\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n}}\n\n'''Cleber Machado''' ([[June]] 25th, [[1937]], [[Porto Alegre]]) is a [[Brazilian]] [[artist]], [[sculptor]] and [[painter]]. Today he lives and works in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. Exhibits individually since [[1971]] and in group since [[1968]]. The artist's [[literature]] includes texts by leading critics. He received several national and international awards and his work is part of important public and private collections.\nSon of Marina Machado Neto e Jo\u00e3o Pedro Pereira Neto, in [[1960]], Cleber moves with the family to [[Rio de Janeiro]], where he joins the student movement, alongside of his friends and also artists of the School of Fine Arts of Rio, [[Artur Barrio]] and [[Rubens Gerchman]]. \nIn [[1968]], amid demonstrations and the National Salon of [[Modern Art]], he is arrested and released within 24 hours - influenced by his father\u00b4s friend. The fright took him away from street demonstrations, but did not take his political interest and engagement. \nPrior to expressing himself as a sculptor, while living in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santa_Teresa_(bairro_do_Rio_de_Janeiro) Santa Tereza], Cleber began designing and producing [[jewelry]] in [[silver]] and [[acrylic]]. This excursion earned him the Jewelry Research award of the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo]. Years later, he resumes jewelry production, this time strongly influenced by [[sculpture]], with the creation of the Sculpture to Wear Collection, composed of true sculptures to be worn on fingers as rings.\nBetween [[1970]] and [[1974]], he had a studio in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Botafogo Botafogo], where he taught several courses and, at the invitation of the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo], participated in the [[Bras\u00edlia]] Room, where his work was acquired by the President [[Juscelino Kubitschek]] to compose the collection of the future [[Brazilian]] Art Museum, built in the federal capital. \nAfter a visit to [[Guaratiba]], a beach 40 kilometers from Rio, where he resumed an old passion for submarine hunting, he moves to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] and performs an exhibition on the shores of [[Ibirapuera Park]] Lake with [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Museu_de_Arte_Moderna_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo MAM-SP]. From [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] he embarks for a period in [[New York]] and next settles for three years in [[Mexico City]] where he presents his installation \"Archeology of the Year 4000\" (according to him, a great responsibility, since his work was exhibited shortly after the closing of [[Henry Moore]]\u00b4s exhibition.\nBack to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], Cleber builds a studio in the neighborhood of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A3o_Crist%C3%B3v%C3%A3o_(bairro_do_Rio_de_Janeiro) S\u00e3o Critov\u00e3o] where he works for the next two years. His participation at the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo 20th International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo] is highlighted by \u201cEarth, Water and Air\u201d performance, where a helicopter simulates the presence and landing of a UFO in [[Ibirapuera Park]] lake. In early 90s, moves back to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] and, once recovered of a period of depression, resumes vigorously his original language, as he likes to call it, \u201coneiric geometry\u201d. His comeback is highlighted by an exposition in the [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casa_das_Rosas House of Roses Garden] (currently [[Haroldo de Campos]] Poetry Space).\n\n== Individual Expositions ==\n\n[[File:Cleber Machado - Miragem I, II e III, 1988.JPG|thumb|border|280px|left|Cleber Machado - Miragem I, II e III, 1988]]\n\n*1971 - Rio de Janeiro Art Museum - MAM Rio\n*1980 \u2013 S\u00e3o Paulo Modern Art Museum - MASP\n*1983 - Museo de Arte Moderno - M\u00e9xico\n*1984 - Rio de Janeiro Art Museum- MAM Rio\n*1997/98 \u2013 House of Roses - S\u00e3o Paulo\n*1999 - Ricardo Camargo Gallery - S\u00e3o Paulo\n*2000 \u2013 The Greenhouse - S\u00e3o Paulo\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n== Collective Expositions ==\n[[File:Niomar Moniz Sodr\u00e9 Bittencourt.jpg|thumb|border|350px| Cleber Machado and Niomar Moniz Sodr\u00e9 Bittencourt]]\n\n*1968 a 1971 - National Salon of Modern Art - Brazil\n*1970 - BankBoston - Brazilian Contemporary Art - Rio de Janeiro - Brazil\n*1970 - Pre-Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brasil\n*1971 - XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1971 \u2013 Pan American Festival of Culture - Cali - Colombia\n*1972 - Brazil Plastic 72 - Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brasil\n*1972 - 1991 - Brazilian Sculpture Overview - MAM - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1975 - XIII International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1979 - XV International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1979 - Alternative Space \"Galp\u00e3o\"- S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1982 \u2013 12th International Sculpture Conference - San Francisco - EUA\n*1982 - 100 Years of Brazilian Sculpture - MASP - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n*1987 - Brazilian Contemporary Art - Trends - Rio de Janeiro - Brasil\n*1989 - XX International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo - Special Events, S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil  \n*1991 - Montesanti Gallery, International Art Fair, Bogot\u00e1 - Colombia\n*1991 - International Biennial of Makurazaki - Japan\n*1996 - Brazilian Museum of Sculpture - Sao Paulo - Brazil\n*1998 - Campinas Contemporary Art Museum - Master's Touch - S\u00e3o Paulo - Brazil\n\n== New York Project==\n<gallery>\nFile:ProjectoOctopus2.jpg|\nFile:ProjetoOctopus1.jpg|\nFile:Machado3ny.jpg|\n</gallery>\n'''Octopus'''<br>\n\nAs [[Pierre Restany]] said, Cleber's [[art critic]] and personal friend, in a written text by him in [[1982]], \u201c... Machado is indeed a message bearer. He conceived a whole program of interventions, from which \u201cOctopus\u201d is the starting point to give his art the existential span of a vital phenomenon. Look into [[New York City]] sky the evolution of a giant octopus. What will be the reaction of people around a corner? Imagination takes power among the skyscrapers of [[Wall Street]], caresses the [[Statue of Liberty]]. More than art in freedom, Machado tries to grab our interest in our essential freedom of being. His dream, if we share it, is a call to order, to existential order, to the law of the great nature.\u201d\n\n== S\u00e3o Paulo Project ==\n<gallery>\nFile:20_Bienal_Internacional_de_S\u00e3o_Paulo.jpg|[http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 20a Bienal Internacional de S\u00e3o Paulo]\nFile:Disco_-_1989.jpg| [http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 Projeto S\u00e3o Paulo - 1989],p.77\nFile:\" Um sonho e uma chamda a ordem\".jpg| [http://issuu.com/bienal/docs/nameb88904 Projeto S\u00e3o Paulo - 1989],p.77\nFile:Cleber_e_Pierre.jpg|[[Pierre Restany]]\n</gallery>\n\n'''An UFO in S\u00e3o Paulo'''<br>\n\nTo be presented in the Special Events of [https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienal_Internacional_de_Arte_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo#20%C2%AA_Bienal_de_S%C3%A3o_Paulo_(1989) 20th International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo] ([[1989]]), Cleber Machado prepares an urban interference from outer world. From [[Congonhas Airport]]  (SP), a helicopter disguised as an UFO takes off, equipped with 20 green and blue light beams. The \"disk\" flies over the city for about 40 minutes, describing symmetrical routes and spiraling down over the [[Ibirapuera Park]] lake. According to Cleber, the purpose of this interference is to enable a dive of fantasy into reality, provoking individuals, stimulating them into new sensations or a new perception of reality.\n\n== Selected Collections == \n[[File:Esfera..jpg|thumb|border|240px|right|Esfera.]]\n\n*Rio de Janeiro Modern Art Museum - MAM Rio\n*S\u00e3o Paulo Modern Art Museum - MAM SP\n*Museo de Arte Moderno - M\u00e9xico\n*Brazilian Art Museum from Armando \u00c1lvares Penteado Foundation - MAB FAAP - SP\n*Museo Rayo - Roldenibe Del Vale - Colombia\n*Brazilian Art Museum - Bras\u00edlia - Brasil\n*Latin American Art Center - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Museo de Arte Americano - Man\u00e1gua - Nicar\u00e1gua\n*Stado of S\u00e3o Paulo Archive - Brasil\n*Museo de Arte Moderna - La Tertulia - Cali - Col\u00f4mbia\n*Museo Casa Del Lago - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Nanmeikan Modern Art - Makurazaki - Jap\u00e3o\n*Museo El Chopo - M\u00e9xico - DF\n*Londrina Art Museum - Paran\u00e1 - Brasil\n\n== Awards ==\n[[File:Cleber Machado - \u00c1rvore, 1991.JPG|thumb|border|240px|right|Cleber Machado - \u00c1rvore, 1991]]\n\n*1970 Brazilian Contemporary Art - Bankboston\u2028 \n*1971 Jewelry Research - XI International Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil\u2028 \n*1972 Research - I National Biennial of S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil\u2028 \n*1991 Special Sculpture - II International Biennial of Makurazaki, Japan\n\n== External Links ==\n[[File:Desenho de Cleber por Julio Larraz.jpg|thumb|border|250px|left|Desenho de Cleber por Julio Larraz]]\n\n\n*[http://www.art-bonobo.com/artes/clebermachado/welcome.html Art Bonobo]\n*[http://www.bolsadearte.com/artistas/perfil/id/399/ Bolsa de Arte]\n*[http://www.espacoarte.com.br/artistas/cleber-machado?id=518# Galeria Espa\u00e7o Arte]\n*[http://mam.org.br/visite/jardim-de-esculturas/ MAM - Jardins das Esculturas]\n*[http://www.rcamargoarte.com.br/expo/?expo=65 Ricardo Camargo Galeria]\n*[http://enciclopedia.itaucultural.org.br/pessoa26332/cleber-machado/Enciclop\u00e9dia Ita\u00fa Cultural]\n*[https://oscardambrosio.com.br/artistas/399/cleber-machado/Oscar D'Ambrosio]\n*[https://mam.org.br/en/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2014/06/MitologiasDEF.pdf/Mitologias MAM-SP]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixinglinks to disambiguation pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleber_Machado_Neto_-_Sculptor"}
{"title_page": "List of Warrant members", "text_new": "[[Warrant (American band)|Warrant]] is an American [[glam metal]] band from [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. Formed in 1984, the group originally included vocalist and acoustic guitarist [[Adam Shore]], lead guitarist [[Josh Lewis (guitarist)|Josh Lewis]], rhythm guitarist [[Erik Turner]], bassist Chris Vincent and drummer Max Asher, although Vincent was replaced after only a few months by [[Jerry Dixon (musician)|Jerry Dixon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jerry-dixon-mn0000327495/biography |title=Jerry Dixon: Biography & History |last=Harris |first=Craig |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Shore and Asher left in September 1986, with Turner bringing in [[Jani Lane]] and [[Steven Sweet]] from the group Plain Jane as their replacements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.loudmag.com.au/features/jani-lane-gone-soon/ |title=Jani Lane: Gone Too Soon |last=Giffin |first=Brian |work=Loud Magazine |date=August 12, 2011 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> The following March, [[Joey Allen]] replaced Lewis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vqpr.com/warrantpress-body.htm |title=\"Warrant\" Announces New Band Line-Up For 2004 |publisher=V.Q. Promotions |date=February 16, 2004 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Warrant released its debut album ''[[Dirty Rotten Filthy Stinking Rich]]'' in 1989, which was followed by ''[[Cherry Pie (album)|Cherry Pie]]'' the following year and ''[[Dog Eat Dog (Warrant album)|Dog Eat Dog]]'' in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/warrant-mn0000193963/biography |title=Warrant: Biography & History |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Lane briefly left Warrant in March 1993 to start a solo career, but within 18 months had returned to the band.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/warrant-guitarist-talks-about-jani-lane-s-passing/ |title=Warrant Guitarist Talks About Jani Lane's Passing |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=August 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPrior to Lane's return, Allen also left in May 1994, followed by Sweet the following month; later in the year, they were replaced by [[Kingdom Come (band)|Kingdom Come]]'s [[Rick Steier]] and [[James Kottak]], respectively.<ref name=\"underrated\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rawrootsrock.com.au/?os_articles=jani-lane-an-under-rated-rock-legend |title=Jani Lane \u2013 An under-rated Rock Legend |website=Raw Roots Rock |date=September 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Kottak only remained for two years, with Bobby Borg taking his place after the release and touring of ''[[Ultraphobic]]''.<ref name=\"underrated\"/> Borg left in 1997 and was replaced on tour by Vik Foxx and later Danny Wagner, the latter of whom had previously played keyboards for the group.<ref name=\"AOR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aordreamer.com/show_bios.php?artist_id=318 |title=Warrant: \"Down Boys\" |website=AORDreamer.com |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Steier and Wagner both subsequently left the band in early 2000.<ref name=\"AOR\"/> Replacing Steier with [[Billy Morris (guitarist)|Billy Morris]] and Wagner with [[Mike Fasano (musician)|Mike Fasano]], Warrant released ''[[Under the Influence (Warrant album)|Under the Influence]]'', an album of [[cover version]]s, in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sleazeroxx.com/interviews/billy-morris-of-tuff-interview-part-2-of-3/ |title=Billy Morris of Tuff Interview (Part 2 of 3) |last=Troyan |first=Greg |website=Sleaze Roxx |date=October 9, 2015 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> On April 2, 2003, Fasano was fired from the band by Lane, with Kevin Phares of the vocalist's solo band taking his place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bravewords.com/news/warrant-drummer-released |title=Warrant - Drummer Released! |work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]] |date=April 3, 2003 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nLane left Warrant for a second time in January 2004 to focus on his solo career, with the group announcing the return of Allen, Fasano and the addition of new frontman [[Jaime St. James]] the following month.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/warrant-announce-new-lineup/ |title=Warrant Announce New Lineup |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=February 15, 2004 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> By March, Fasano had been replaced by the returning Sweet, marking a reunion of the band's classic lineup with the exception of Lane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/warrant-drummer-steven-sweet-rejoins-the-fold/ |title=Warrant: Drummer Steven Sweet Rejoins The Fold |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=March 17, 2004 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> ''[[Born Again (Warrant album)|Born Again]]'', the first Warrant album without Lane, was released in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/born-again-mw0000734589 |title=Born Again - Warrant: Songs, Reviews, Credits |last=Viglione |first=Joe |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> In early 2008, Lane returned to front Warrant for a third time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/warrant-reunites-with-singer-jani-lane-first-photo-released/ |title=Warrant Reunites With Singer Jani Lane: First Photo Released |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=January 29, 2008 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> The reunion lasted less than a year, however, as Lane left for a final time in September and was replaced by former [[Lynch Mob (band)|Lynch Mob]] frontman Robert Mason.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/warrant-parts-ways-with-singer-jani-lane-again/ |title=Warrant Parts Ways With Singer Jani Lane... Again |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=September 5, 2008 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref> Lane later died on August 11, 2011 of acute alcohol poisoning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/warrant-jani-lane-death-anniversary/ |title=Six Years Ago: Warrant Singer Jani Lane Dies |last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |website=[[Loudwire]] |date=August 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n===Current===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" width=100%\n|-\n!width=\"75\"|Image\n!width=\"120\"|Name\n!width=\"90\"|Years active\n!width=\"160\"|Instruments\n!Release contributions\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Erik_Turner.jpg |bSize=250 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=48 |oLeft=48 }}\n|[[Erik Turner]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1984\u2013present\n|{{hlist|rhythm and lead guitars|backing vocals}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|all [[Warrant discography|Warrant releases]]\n|-\n|\n|[[Jerry Dixon (musician)|Jerry Dixon]]\n|{{hlist|bass|backing vocals}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Steven Sweet]]\n|{{hlist|1986\u20131994|2004\u2013present}}\n|{{hlist|drums|percussion|backing vocals}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|all Warrant releases from ''[[Dirty Rotten Filthy Stinking Rich]]'' (1989) to ''[[Dog Eat Dog (Warrant album)|Dog Eat Dog]]'' (1992), and from ''[[Born Again (Warrant album)|Born Again]]'' (2006) onwards\n|-\n|\n|[[Joey Allen]]\n|{{hlist|1987\u20131994|2004\u2013present}}\n|{{hlist|lead and rhythm guitars|backing vocals}}\n|-\n|\n|Robert Mason\n|2008\u2013present\n|{{hlist|vocals|acoustic guitar|harmonica|piano}}\n|{{hlist|''[[Rockaholic]]'' (2011)|''[[Louder Harder Faster]]'' (2017)}}\n|}\n\n===Former===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" width=100%\n|-\n!width=\"75\"|Image\n!width=\"120\"|Name\n!width=\"90\"|Years active\n!width=\"160\"|Instruments\n!Release contributions\n|-\n|\n|Josh Lewis\n|1984\u20131987\n|{{hlist|lead and rhythm guitars|backing vocals}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"|none\n|-\n|\n|[[Adam Shore]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1984\u20131986\n|{{hlist|vocals|acoustic guitar}}\n|-\n|\n|Max Asher\n|{{hlist|drums|percussion}}\n|-\n|\n|Chris Vincent\n|1984\n|{{hlist|bass|backing vocals}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Jani Lane]]\n|{{hlist|1986\u20131993|1994\u20132004|2008 {{small|(died 2011)}}}}\n|{{hlist|vocals|acoustic guitar|keyboards|percussion}}\n|all Warra